SIMPLE: tun
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Tun
<hw>Tun</hw> <pr>(t⟦ucr⟧n)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS.
<ets>tunne</ets>. See <er>Ton</er> a weight.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A
large cask; an oblong vessel bulging in the middle, like a pipe or
puncheon, and girt with hoops; a wine cask.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Brewing)</fld> <def>A fermenting vat.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A certain measure for liquids, as for wine, equal to
two pipes, four hogsheads, or 252 gallons. In different countries, the
tun differs in quantity.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Com.)</fld> <def>A weight of 2,240 pounds. See
<er>Ton</er>.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>An indefinite large quantity.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A <qex>tun</qex> of man in thy large bulk is writ.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>A drunkard; -- so called humorously, or in
contempt.</def> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any shell belonging to
<gen>Dolium</gen> and allied genera; -- called also
<altname>tun-shell</altname>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tun</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Tun
<hw>Tun</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Tunned</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Tunning</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To put into tuns, or casks.</def>
<rj><au>Boyle.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tuna</ent>⟦br⟧
